Root Cause Analysis
Primary root cause:
Installation of incompatible generic audio drivers via third-party driver updater utilities. These drivers overwrote platform-specific components required for audio enhancement and monitoring integration.
Specifically affected components:
• Audio processing service components
• Audio framework services
• Platform-specific driver extensions
• Enhancement service bindings
Driver store contamination resulted in persistent conflicts and improper dependency resolution.

Remediation Procedure
Phase 1 — Research and Driver Validation
Validated correct driver packages using trusted sources. Ensured compatibility with:
• Windows 11
• Platform-specific motherboard
• Audio enhancement ecosystem
Phase 2 — Complete Removal of Existing Audio Stack
Performed full removal of corrupted audio drivers and related software.
Application-Level Removal:
• Removed installed audio applications via Settings → Apps → Installed Apps and Control Panel → Programs and Features
Driver Store Cleanup:
• Executed DriverStore Explorer (or equivalent) as Administrator
• Removed all relevant audio driver packages and residual service entries
Hidden Device and Software Component Removal:
• Enabled hidden devices in Device Manager
• Removed residual audio service components
• Restarted system to finalize cleanup
Phase 3 — Clean Installation of Platform-Specific Audio Drivers
• Downloaded verified platform-specific driver package
• Executed installation with elevated privileges
• Installed drivers, restored services and framework
• Restarted system
Phase 4 — Audio Applications Installation
• Installed audio enhancement and monitoring applications via verified sources
• Ensured all components updated to latest compatible versions
• Restarted system

